{{Multiple issues|
{{Refimprove|date=April 2016}}
{{fanpov|date=April 2016}}
}}
[[Professional wrestling]] has accrued a considerable nomenclature throughout its existence.<ref name=torch>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/insiderglossary.shtml|title=Torch Glossary of Insider Terms|publisher=PWTorch.com|accessdate=July 10, 2007|year=2000|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606073745/http://www.pwtorch.com/insiderglossary.shtml|archivedate=June 6, 2011}}</ref> Much of it stems from the industry's origins in the days of [[carnival]]s and circuses.<ref name=amspeech/> In the past, professional wrestlers used such terms in the presence of fans so as not to reveal the {{gli|work|worked}} nature of the business.<ref name=torch/><ref name=amspeech/> In recent years, widespread discussion on the [[Internet]] has popularized these terms.<ref name=torch/> Many of the terms refer to the financial aspects of professional wrestling in addition to in-ring terms.<ref name=amspeech>{{cite journal|last=Kerrick|first=George E.|date=Summer 1980|title=The Jargon of Professional Wrestling|journal=American Speech|volume=55|issue=2|pages=142–145|doi=10.2307/3050508}}</ref>
{{Dynamic list|date=August 2008}}
{{compact ToC|notesfirst=yes|refs=yes|extlinks=yes}}

== A ==
{{term|A-show}}
{{defn|1= A wrestling event where a company's biggest {{gli|draw|draws}} wrestle.<ref name=torch/> ''Compare {{gli|b-show|B-show}} and {{gli|c-show|C-show}}''.}}
{{term|A-team}}
{{defn|1= A group of a wrestling promotion's top stars who wrestle at an A-show.<ref name=torch/> ''Compare {{gli|b-team|B-team}}''.}}
{{term|abort}}
{{defn|1= To suddenly discontinue a {{gli|feud}}, {{gli|angle}}, or {{gli|gimmick}} due to a lack of fan interest, usually without explanation.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|ace}}
{{defn|1= A term typically only used in Japanese ''[[puroresu]]'' for a wrestler designated as the face of the promotion. Not necessarily the same as the top champion. Examples of aces include [[Hayabusa (wrestler)|Hayabusa]] in [[Frontier Martial-Arts Wrestling]], [[Hiroshi Tanahashi]] in [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]] and [[Suwama]] in [[All Japan Pro Wrestling]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/ROH_News_29/article_84228.shtml|title=ROH news: New Japan's top star announced for ROH vs. New Japan tour, ROH releases "Field of Honor" details|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=April 1, 2015|accessdate=June 11, 2016|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nikkansports.com/battle/news/f-bt-tp0-20111219-878523.html|script-title=ja:全日諏訪魔ＶＳ大日関本シングル対決実現|date=December 19, 2011|accessdate=June 11, 2016|work=[[Nikkan Sports]]|language=Japanese}}</ref> ''Compare {{gli|face of the company}}''.}}
{{term|agent}}
{{defn|1={{Ghat|Also '''producer'''.}}
A management employee, often a former wrestler (though it can be a current wrestler), who helps wrestlers set up matches, plan storylines, give criticisms on matches, and relay instructions from the {{gli|book|bookers}}. Agents often act as a liaison between wrestlers and higher-level management and sometimes may also help in training younger wrestlers. They are referred to by [[WWE]] as "producers".}}
{{term|alliance}}
{{defn|1= A cooperative relationship developed between two or more wrestlers, whether wrestling as a [[tag team]] or in individual matches. Differentiates from a {{gli|stable}} as the wrestlers are not packaged together, but are presented as a group of individuals working together for a common goal. Alliances are often formed for the specific purpose of retaining titles between the members of the alliance, or to counter a specific foe or group of foes. The formation of an alliance can be a storyline of its own.<ref>Nicholas Sammond, ''Steel Chair to the Head: The Pleasure and Pain of Professional Wrestling'' (2004).</ref>}}
{{term|angle}}
{{defn|1= A fictional storyline. An angle usually begins when one wrestler attacks another (physically or verbally), which results in revenge.<ref name=amspeech/> An angle may be as small as a single match or a vendetta that lasts for years. It is not uncommon to see an angle become [[retroactive continuity|retcon]]ned due to it not getting {{gli|over}} with the fans, or if one of the wrestlers currently involved in the angle is fired.}}
{{term|Apter mag}}
{{defn|1= An old-style professional wrestling magazine that sticks to {{gli|kayfabe}} articles.<ref name=torch/> The term refers to the magazines at one time connected to journalist [[Bill Apter]], such as ''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]''.<ref name=torch/>}}

== B ==
{{term|B-show}}
{{defn|1= A wrestling event featuring the middle and lower-level talent of a wrestling promotion. Sometimes includes well-known wrestlers making a return or finishing up their career.<ref name=torch/> ''Compare {{gli|a-show|A-show}} and {{gli|c-show|C-show}}''.}}
{{term|B-team}}
{{defn|1= The group of wrestlers on a {{gli|b-show|B-show}}.<ref name=torch/> Frequently, the B-team will wrestle at a venue the same night wrestlers on the {{gli|A-team}} are wrestling in a different event, although a promotion will sometimes schedule an event with B-team wrestlers to test a new market. ''Compare {{gli|a-team|A-team}}''.}}
{{term|babyface}}
{{defn|1= ''See {{gli|face}}''.}}
{{term|beat down}}
{{defn|1=[[File:The Shield Teamwork.jpg|thumb|[[The Shield (professional wrestling)|The Shield]] performing a {{gli|beat down}} on [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]]]]
A situation in which a wrestler or other performer is the recipient of a one-sided beating, usually by a group of wrestlers.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|blading|content=blading {{anchor|juicing}}}}
{{defn|1={{Main|Blading (professional wrestling)}}
{{Ghat|Also '''juicing''', '''gigging''' and '''getting color'''.}}
A wrestler intentionally cutting themselves to provoke bleeding to {{gli|sell}} the opponent's offense.}}
{{term|blind tag}}
{{defn|no=1|1= A tag made in a [[tag team]] match where the wrestler on the apron tags his partner unbeknownst to them or without their consent.}}
{{defn|no=2|1= A tag where the tagger's opponent is unaware a tag has occurred, leaving them open to a blindside attack. Most often occurs when the partner in the ring is thrown against the ropes or backed into their own corner.}}
{{term|blown spot}}
{{defn|1= ''See {{gli|missed spot}}''.}}
{{term|blow off}}
{{defn|1= The final match in a {{gli|feud}}.<ref name=torch/> While the involved wrestlers often move onto new feuds, sometimes it is the final match in the promotion for one or more of the wrestlers.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|blow up}}
{{defn|1= To become exhausted during a match.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|book}}{{anchor|Booker}}
{{defn|1={{Ghat|Also '''booker''' and '''booking'''.}}
To determine and schedule the events of a wrestling {{gli|card}}. The person in charge of setting up matches and writing {{gli|angle|angles}} is a "booker".<ref name=torch/> It is the wrestling equivalent of a [[screenwriter]]. A booker can also be described as someone who recruits and hires talent to work in a particular promotion.  The [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Iowa]] defined a booker in 1956 as "[...] any person who, for a fee or commission, arranges with a promoter or promoters for the performance of wrestlers in professional wrestling exhibitions".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wrestlingperspective.com/legal/consentdecree.html|title=United States v. National Wrestling Alliance (consent decree)|first=Judge William F.|last=Riley|authorlink=William F. Riley|date=October 15, 1956|work=[[United States District Court for the Southern District of Iowa]]|publisher=As hosted at ''Wrestling Perspective''|accessdate=September 17, 2011}}</ref> Booking is also the term a wrestler uses to describe a scheduled match or appearance on a wrestling show.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|botch}}
{{defn|1={{Main|Botch (professional wrestling)}}
Something (usually a scripted move or spoken line) which does not go as planned due to a mistake.}}
{{term|broadway}}
{{defn|1={{Ghat|Also '''going broadway'''.}}
A match that ends in a time limit draw.}}
{{term|bump}}
{{defn|1= To fall on the mat or ground.<ref name=torch/><ref>Foley, Mick. Have A Nice Day: A Tale of Blood and Sweatsocks (p.65)</ref> A flat back bump is a bump in which a wrestler lands solidly on their back with high impact, spread over as much surface as possible.<ref name=torch/> A "phantom bump" occurs when a wrestler or referee takes a bump without a plausible reason (usually due to a {{gli|botch}} or other mistake).<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|burial|2=burial}}
{{defn|1={{Ghat|Also '''bury''' and '''buried'''.}}
The {{gli|work|worked}} lowering (relegation) of a wrestler's status in the eyes of the fans. The opposite of a {{gli|push}}, it is the act of a promoter or {{gli|booker}} causing a wrestler to lose popularity and credibility through means such as forcing them to lose in {{gli|squash}} matches, losing continuously, allowing opponents to no-{{gli|sell}} or {{gli|kick out}} of said wrestler's {{gli|finisher}}, or forcing them to participate in unentertaining or degrading storylines. A burial is often used a form of punishment due to real-life backstage disagreements between the wrestler and the booker, the wrestler falling out of favor with the company, or sometimes to demote an unpopular performer or {{gli|gimmick}}.}}
{{term|business}}
{{defn|1= Professional wrestling; instead of "profession" or "sport".<ref name=amspeech/>}}
{{term|bust open}}
{{defn|1= To start to bleed, usually from the head after being hit with something like a chair, and typically (but not always) after {{gli|blading}}.}}

== C ==
{{term|C-show}}
{{defn|1= An event featuring the lowest level of talent in a promotion, most notably rookies and entry-level talent. Often used as a derogatory adjective. ''Compare {{gli|a-show|A-show}} and {{gli|b-show|B-show}}''.}}
{{term|call}}
{{defn|1= To instruct the other wrestler of what is going to happen in the match.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|call it in the ring}}
{{defn|1= To make up moves and storytelling in a match on the fly, rather than rehearse them in advance. It is essentially the wrestling equivalent of [[improvisational theatre]].}}
{{term|card}}
{{defn|1= The lineup of the matches that will be staged at a given venue for a given performance.<ref name=torch/> The card is generally performed in a roughly inverse order to the way in which it might be printed for posters or other promotional materials. The major matches between well-known opponents are said to be "top of the card" or the {{gli|main event}} and generally go on last, while the preliminary matches between lesser-known opponents are said to be the "undercard".}}
{{term|carpenter}}
{{defn|1= A term for a wrestler whose purpose is to use their in-ring abilities to make their opponents look as good and strong as possible. This is different from an {{gli|jobber|enhancement talent}} in that a wrestler is used as a carpenter because they are recognized as having great in-ring abilities and experience. Often (but not always) a carpenter is an older, more experienced wrestler, tasked with making less experienced wrestlers (often in the beginning stages of receiving a {{gli|push}}) look like a credible threat going into their next {{gli|program}}. In modern times, a carpenter is also used when a company is preparing to present a recent signee who may not be familiar to the audience, in an effort to help the wrestler best showcase their abilities.}}
{{term|carry}}
{{defn|1= The act of one wrestler guiding a typically less experienced or skilled performer through a match. A "carry job" refers to a match or {{gli|angle}} in which a particularly skilled performer is able to make an inferior wrestler look good, or is perceived to be doing all the work.}}
{{term|championship advantage}}
{{defn|1={{Ghat|Also '''champion's advantage'''.}}
A reigning champion's right to retain a title, should he or she lose a championship match by [[countout]] or [[Professional wrestling#Disqualification|disqualification]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jrsbarbq.com/blog/46940|title=Samoa Joe on Ross Report podcast tonight|last=Ross|first=Jim|authorlink=Jim Ross|date=May 5, 2015|publisher=JR's BarBQ|access-date=July 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/eliminationchamber/2013/the-rock-cm-punk |title=WWE Champion The Rock def. CM Punk |last=Clapp |first=John |date=February 17, 2013 |publisher=[[WWE]] |access-date=July 30, 2016 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130221024247/http://www.wwe.com/shows/eliminationchamber/2013/the-rock-cm-punk |archivedate=February 21, 2013 |df= }}</ref>}}
{{term|cheap heat}}
{{defn|1= The incitement of a negative crowd reaction by insulting the crowd en-masse, typically by bringing up something unrelated to the wrestling business (such as mocking a local town or sports team), usually used in a negative light.<ref name=torch/><ref name=amspeech/> ''Compare {{gli|cheap pop}}''.}}
{{term|cheap pop}}
{{defn|1= The incitement of a positive crowd reaction by "kissing up" to the crowd. {{gli|heel|Heels}} often follow the same principle, but in reverse to get booed. ''Compare {{gli|cheap heat}}''.}}
{{term|cheap shot}}
{{defn|1= An underhanded tactic, such as a [[Low blow (professional wrestling)|low blow]] or a {{gli|foreign object}} to get an advantage over an opponent.}}
{{term|clean finish}}
{{defn|1= A match ending without cheating, outside interference, or any type of controversy, usually in the center of the ring after executing a {{gli|finisher}}. ''Compare {{gli|Dusty finish}} and {{gli|screwjob}}''.}}
{{term|clean wrestling}}
{{defn|1= Matches pitting two {{gli|face|faces}} with no storyline animosity against each other, both obeying the rules throughout. Such matches are characterized by an emphasis on displaying [[technical wrestling]] skill instead of {{gli|work|working}} the audience and a general air of sportsmanship. Although a staple of British and Japanese wrestling, it is uncommon in North America. One notable "clean" match which took place in North America is [[Hulk Hogan]] vs. [[The Ultimate Warrior]] at [[WrestleMania VI]] in 1990.<ref>''Whatever Happened to Gorgeous George'' by Joe Jares, Tempo Books, 1974, p. 85.</ref>}}
{{term|closet champion}}
{{defn|1= A titleholder (usually a {{gli|heel}}) who ducks top-flight matches, cheats to win (often by managerial interference), and—when forced to wrestle good opponents—deliberately causes themself to be disqualified (since titles often do not change hands by [[Disqualification (professional wrestling)|disqualification]]) to retain the title.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|color}}
{{defn|1= The amount of bloodshed in a match.<ref name=torch/><ref name=race106>Harley Race, Ricky Steamboat, Les Thatcher. The Professional Wrestlers' Workout & Instructional Guide (p.106)</ref><ref name="Stone Cold Steve Austin p.90">Stone Cold Steve Austin. ''The Stone Cold Truth'' (p.90)</ref>}}
{{term|comeback}}
{{defn|1= A match in which a wrestler is being dominated and then manages to turn things around and fight back successfully. Usually done by {{gli|face|faces}} to earn sympathy. The expression "feeding a comeback" refers to something {{gli|heels}} do to increase the dramatic impact of a comeback.<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2V060IwjJh4&t=1m|title=X-Pac on: Yokozuna|date=31 December 2014|work=YouTube}}</ref> May become a {{gli|false comeback}} if ended prematurely. Known informally as "Hulking up" in reference to [[Hulk Hogan]]'s signature comeback trait.}}
{{term|crimson mask}}
{{defn|1= A face covered in blood, comparable to a mask.}}
{{term|cross-promotion}}
{{defn|1= An event which occurs when two or more rival promotions put together one {{gli|card}} or wrestling event. Some promoters have used cross-promotion style {{gli|angle|angles}} to further interest. Cross-promotion dates back to the early days of wrestling as challenges between rival promoters in the same area often occurred.}}
{{term|curtain jerker}}
{{defn|1=''See {{gli|jerk the curtain}}''.}}

== D ==
{{term|dark match}}
{{defn|1= A non-televised match at a televised show (''compare {{gli|house show}}'').<ref name=torch/> A dark match before the show is often used to test new talent or warm up the crowd.<ref name=torch/> A dark match after the show typically features {{gli|main event}} level wrestlers, in order to sell more tickets and send the crowd home happy, without affecting TV storylines.}}
{{term|deathmatch wrestling}}
{{defn|1={{see also|Hardcore wrestling}}
The bloodiest and most violent form of {{gli|hardcore wrestling}}, popular in Japan, Mexico, and some parts of the United States. In deathmatch wrestling, many of the traditional rules of professional wrestling are not enforced and the usage of objects such as barbed wire, panes of glass, fluorescent light tubes, weed whackers, among others, occurs. Deathmatches are typically much bloodier and more violent than the typical wrestling contest.}}
{{term|dirt sheet}}
{{defn|1= An insider newsletter (or website) in the professional wrestling business. Sometimes written in a negative tone or as a means to "get dirt".<ref>Stone Cold Steve Austin. ''The Stone Cold Truth'' (p.83)</ref>}}
{{term|double team}}
{{defn|1=[[File:Rougeau Brothers' Finishing Move.jpg|thumb|[[The Fabulous Rougeaus]] performing a {{gli|double team}} [[professional wrestling double-team maneuvers|maneuver]]]]
A tactic used in a [[tag team]] match when both members of a tag team gang up on one of the opponents, or a move that involves two wrestlers working in unison.}}
{{term|double turn}}
{{defn|1= The occurrence when both the {{gli|face}} and the {{gli|heel}} switch roles during an {{gli|angle}} or a match. Arguably the most famous example is that of [[Stone Cold Steve Austin]] versus [[Bret Hart]] at [[WrestleMania 13]], where Austin entered as a heel and Hart entered as a face, but due to Austin fighting on through blood and passing out to a move by Hart, the two switched roles to end the match.}}
{{term|draw}}
{{defn|1= A wrestler or {{gli|program}} that attracts the attention of the audience; someone fans are willing to pay to see. Derived from the term "drawing money", meaning the wrestler makes money for the promotion.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|dream match}}
{{defn|1= A match that fans wish they could see. Derived from the term "in your dreams".}}
{{term|drop}}
{{defn|1= To lose a match or championship (the loser agreed to drop the match to the winner).}}
{{term|Dusty finish}}
{{defn|1= A {{gli|finish}} in which the {{gli|face}} appears to win a big match, but the decision is later reversed due to some sort of technicality, such as {{gli|interference}} by other {{gli|heel|heels}} to save the heel champion, as, in most federations, the title could not change hands on such a [[Disqualification (professional wrestling)|disqualification]]. It can also refer to an ambiguous finish to a match where neither wrestler can claim to be the winner.<ref name=torch/> The "Dusty" in the term refers to [[Dusty Rhodes (wrestler)|Dusty Rhodes]], who {{gli|book|booked}} many such finishes in [[National Wrestling Alliance]] (NWA) and later in [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW).<ref name=torch/>}}

== E ==
{{term|enforcer}}
{{defn|1=[[File:The Authority plus Kane and Randy Orton.jpg|thumb|[[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]] (second left) as {{gli|enforcer}} for [[The Authority (professional wrestling)|The Authority]]]]
A (typically larger) wrestler who accompanies another to matches and acts as a bodyguard.<ref name=torch/> This term was coined by [[Arn Anderson]], whose nickname was "The Enforcer". The term can also refer to an individual who acts in a "[[special guest referee]]" capacity from outside the ring, ostensibly to maintain order.}}
{{term|enhancement talent}}
{{defn|1= ''See {{gli|jobber}}''.}}
{{term|exótico|content=''exótico''}}
{{defn|1={{Main|Exótico}}
A wrestler (typically a Mexican luchador) who competes in drag. Examples of exóticos include: Mexico's [[Pimpinela Escarlata]], America's [[Goldust]], and Japan's [[Yosuke Santa Maria]].}}
{{term|extreme wrestling}}
{{defn|1={{see also|Hardcore wrestling}}
A style of professional wrestling that makes frequent use of {{gli|highspot|highspots}} and weapons. [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]] and [[Combat Zone Wrestling]] are known for using this style.}}

== F ==
{{term|face}}
{{defn|1={{Main|Face (professional wrestling)}}
{{Ghat|Also '''babyface'''.}}
A wrestler who is heroic, who is {{gli|book|booked}} to be cheered by fans.<ref name=torch/> {{gli|heel|Heels}} are the opposite of faces, and faces commonly perform against heels.}}
{{term|face-in-peril}}
{{defn|1={{Ghat|Also '''playing Ricky Morton'''.}}
In a [[tag team]] match, the member of a {{gli|face}} team who is dominated by the {{gli|heel}} team for an extended period of the match. The tactic can be used to help get the crowd behind the face tag team and is usually followed up with a {{gli|hot tag}}. During the 1980s, [[Ricky Morton]] of the [[Rock 'n' Roll Express]] was typically in this position while teaming with [[Robert Gibson (wrestler)|Robert Gibson]]; so much so that "playing Ricky Morton" has become synonymous with the term.}}
{{term|face of the company}}
{{defn|1= A wrestler that represents the wrestling promotion that they are a part of, and frequently appears on merchandise, promotions and television adverts, amongst other things. They can be a top champion, or simply a recognizable wrestler. ''Compare {{gli|ace}}''.}}
{{term|fall}}
{{defn|1= The ending of a match. A fall is obtained by gaining a decision in any manner, normally consisting of a {{gli|pinfall}}, [[Submission (professional wrestling)|submission]], [[countout]], or [[Disqualification (professional wrestling)|disqualification]]. In a [[professional wrestling match types#series variations|two out of three falls match]], or a Mountevans Rules match, a wrestler must gain two decisions to win instead of only one. ''See also {{gli|near-fall}}''.}}
{{term|fallout show}}
{{defn|1= The first televised show after a [[pay-per-view]]. ''Contrast with {{gli|go-home show}}''.}}
{{term|false comeback|content=false comeback {{anchor|hope spot}}}}
{{defn|1={{Ghat|Also '''hope spot'''.}}
A brief offensive flurry by a {{gli|face}}, before losing momentum back to a {{gli|heel}} after being dominated for several minutes.<ref name=torch/> Usually, it occurs before the actual {{gli|comeback}}.}}
{{term|false finish}}
{{defn|1= A {{gli|pinfall}} attempt which is kicked out of, usually after a {{gli|finisher}} or series of high impact moves, and usually kicked out of just before the referee counts to three. This builds crowd anticipation towards the actual finish.}}
{{term|feud}}
{{defn|1={{Main|Feud (professional wrestling)}}
A {{gli|work|staged}} rivalry between multiple wrestlers or groups of wrestlers. They are integrated into ongoing storylines, particularly in events which are televised. Feuds may last for months or even years or be resolved with implausible speed, perhaps during the course of a single match.<ref name="torch"/>}}
{{term|fighting champion}}
{{defn|1= A champion who defends his title often, and with most or all of the outcomes being victory by pinfall or submission.}}
{{term|finish}}
{{defn|1= The planned end of a match.<ref name=torch/> ''See {{gli|clean finish}} and {{gli|Dusty finish}}''.}}
{{term|finisher}}
{{defn|1= A wrestler's signature move that usually leads to the {{gli|pinfall}} or [[Submission (professional wrestling)|submission]].}}
{{term|five moves of doom}}
{{defn|1= A particular combination of moves that a certain wrestler tends to use in every match, often in the same sequence, usually ending with their {{gli|finisher}}. This term is usually used pejoratively, though it was not originally intended so by [[Dave Meltzer]], who coined the term in the 1990s to describe the finishing sequence of [[Bret Hart]], and is most notably used today to describe the common finishing moves of [[John Cena]].}}
{{term|foreign object}}
{{defn|1= A weapon that is not allowed to be used in the match. Usually found under the ring or ringside, in a wrestler's tights, or handed to wrestlers by {{gli|manager|managers}}, interfering wrestlers or (less commonly) audience members. If a foreign object is used behind the referee's back, it usually leads to a {{gli|pinfall}}. However, the same object is typically less effective in a match where it is legal. At one point in [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW)'s history, this was referred to as "international objects" by commentators due to a misunderstanding that WCW owner [[Ted Turner]]'s objections to the use of the word "foreign" applied throughout his media empire, when he intended only to restrict the word's use on his news networks.}}
{{term|free agent}}
{{defn|1= Somewhat similar to professional sports, "free agent" is a term used to describe a professional wrestler who is not under contract to a single major promotion. A wrestler who is a free agent can appear for multiple {{gli|independent promotion|independent promotions}}. The term is also used within the [[WWE]] promotion to describe certain wrestlers who are not exclusive to one of their [[WWE brand extension|brands]], being able to appear and perform on any brand (e.g., [[John Cena]], who became a free agent in 2017).}}

== G ==
{{term|gas}}
{{defn|no=1|1= Steroids.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{defn|no=2|1= Stamina, as in "out of [[Gasoline|gas]]".}}
{{term|gassed}}
{{defn|1= Exhausted or out of breath during a match.}}
{{term|gig}}
{{defn|1= The blade a wrestler uses to cut themself.<ref name=torch/> ''See {{gli|blading}}''.}}
{{term|gimmick}}
{{defn|1=[[File:Irwin R Schyster in 1994.jpg|thumb|[[Mike Rotunda]] used a [[tax collector]] {{gli|gimmick}} as Irwin R. Schyster]]
{{Ghat|{{Main|Gimmick (professional wrestling)}}}}
The character portrayed by a wrestler.  Can also be used to refer specifically to the motif or theme evoked by a character, as indicated by their name, costume or other paraphernalia.}}
{{term|glorified jobber}}
{{defn|1={{Ghat|Also '''jobber to the stars'''.}}
A {{gli|jobber}} who defeats "pure jobbers" as well as mid-card wrestlers in matches, but consistently loses to {{gli|main event}} level wrestlers.}}
{{term|go away heat}}
{{defn|1= When a wrestler, {{gli|heel}} or {{gli|face}}, evokes a negative reaction not through their {{gli|work|working}} of the audience but because the audience are not entertained by the wrestler and do not want to watch them perform. ''Compare {{gli|x-pac heat|X-Pac heat}}''.}}
{{term|go home}}
{{defn|1= To finish a match. One wrestler would tell the other to "go home" when it is time for them to execute the planned ending for their match. Referees may also tell the wrestlers to go home (usually after receiving word to do so from a producer backstage).}}
{{term|go-home show}}
{{defn|1= The final televised show before a [[pay-per-view]] event. So named because the promotion will often have no {{gli|house show|house shows}} in the next few days before the pay-per-view, in order to give the wrestlers a chance to literally go home and rest up so they may bring their A-Game at the pay-per-view. ''Contrast with {{gli|fallout show}}''.}}
{{term|going into business for him/herself}}
{{defn|1= When a wrestler starts working for their own benefit rather than the mutual benefit of themselves and their opponents, typically by refusing to {{gli|sell}}. A type of {{gli|shoot}}.}}
{{term|gold}}
{{defn|1= A championship belt.}}
{{term|go over}}
{{defn|1= To win in a wrestling match.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|Gorilla position}}
{{defn|1= The staging area just behind the curtain where wrestlers come out to the ring, named after [[Gorilla Monsoon]]. The Gorilla Position in [[World Championship Wrestling]] was named after [[Jody Hamilton]] and was commonly referred to as the "Jody Position."}}
{{term|green}}
{{defn|1=  Refers to a wrestler who is in the early stages of their career and, as a result, may be prone to making mistakes because of their inexperience.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|gusher}}
{{defn|1= A deep cut that bleeds a lot,<ref name="Stone Cold Steve Austin p.90"/> usually caused by a mistake while {{gli|blading}}, but can be intentional. An example happened at the [[Judgment Day (2004)|Judgment Day]] PPV in 2004, when [[Eddie Guerrero]] accidentally hit a blood vessel when blading.<ref name=torch/>}}

== H ==
{{term|hardcore wrestling}}
{{defn|1={{Main|Hardcore wrestling}}
{{Ghat|Also '''garbage wrestling'''.}}
A style of wrestling that emphasizes brutality and real violence with matches typically involving minimal [[technical wrestling]], instead focusing on moderate brawling techniques and the use of weapons.}}
{{term|hardway}}
{{defn|1= A wrestler bleeding by any means other than blading, typically from a legitimate strike or {{gli|potato}}.}}
{{term|head drop}}
{{defn|1= A move which, as a result of a {{gli|botch}}, causes the receiver to be dropped on their head, often resulting in a {{gli|legit}} concussion or other injury such as a broken neck. Also, especially in ''[[puroresu]]'', the term can refer to a {{gli|bump}} which is intended to make a move appear as if the receiver landed on his or her head. In reality, the full force of the move is intended to be taken on the upper back and shoulders, though such moves still carry a high degree of legitimate risk with them.}}
{{term|heat}}
{{defn|1={{Ghat|{{Main|Heat (professional wrestling)}}}}
1.&nbsp; Negative reactions (such as booing) from the live fans. When the heat is directed at a {{gli|heel}} this is seen as a good thing, as it means fans are reacting in the desired way.}}
{{defn|no=2|1=Real-life tension or bad feeling between two wrestlers, or a wrestler and the promotion.}}
{{term|heel}}
{{defn|1={{Ghat|{{Main|Heel (professional wrestling)}}}}
A wrestler who is villainous, who is {{gli|book|booked}} to be booed by fans.<ref name=torch/> {{gli|face|Faces}} are the opposite of heels, and heels commonly perform against faces.}}
{{term|highspot}}
{{defn|1=[[File:Lesnarbotch.jpg|thumb|[[Brock Lesnar]] performing a {{gli|highspot}}; a [[Professional wrestling aerial techniques#Shooting star press|shooting star press]] at [[WrestleMania XIX]]]]
A high-stakes move which is perceived to be risky and very dangerous, often legitimately.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|Hollywood}}
{{defn|1= A popular {{gli|heel}} persona based on the idea of a performer having real-world success and fame which transcends the wrestling business. Used by wrestlers such as [[Hulk Hogan]], [[Dwayne Johnson|The Rock]], [[Dave Bautista|Batista]], and [[The Miz]].}}
{{term|hooker}}
{{defn|1= A wrestler with strong legitimate mat-wrestling abilities and an array of match-ending (or in extreme cases, career ending) holds known as "hooks", hence the name.<ref name=torch/> Primarily a holdover from the days where professional wrestling had to maintain {{gli|kayfabe}}, a hooker would be used against a local non-wrestler brawler to enhance the belief that professional wrestling was "real". One of the most famous hookers in wrestling history was world champion [[Lou Thesz]].}}
{{term|hoss}}
{{defn|1= A wrestler who is physically large, but lacks other skills. A match between two large men who use plenty of {{gli|stiff}} strikes is sometimes known as a "hossfest".}}
{{term|hotshot}}
{{defn|1= A rushed {{gli|feud}}, climax of a feud, or big match on television instead of at a [[pay-per-view]] in order to get a short-term boost for business.<ref name=torch/> Also applies to {{gli|angle|angles}} or {{gli|turn|turns}} that are done for shock value rather than acting as a part of an ongoing storyline.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|hot tag}}
{{defn|1= In a [[tag team]] match, the {{gli|face}}'s tag to a fresh partner after several minutes of being dominated by both {{gli|heel|heels}}, usually immediately followed by the freshly tagged partner getting in a quick burst of offense.<ref name=torch/> Often the hot tag happens after several teases (where the other face is enticed into the ring, only to be stopped by the referee and the heels getting away with illegal tactics, or a legal tag being made while the referee is distracted, resulting in the referee forcing the fresh partner out of the ring because "he was not tagged in").}}
{{term|house}}
{{defn|1= The amount of money drawn at a particular event.}}
{{term|house show|content=house show {{anchor|live event}}}}
{{defn|1={{Main|House show}}
{{Ghat|Also '''live event'''.}}
An untelevised event.}}

== I ==
{{term|impromptu match}}
{{defn|1= A match that takes place, specifically on [[pay-per-view]]s, that was not announced on the {{gli|card}} before the event.}}
{{term|independent promotion}}
{{defn|1= {{Main|Independent circuit}}
{{Ghat|Also '''indie promotion'''.}}
A smaller wrestling company that operates at a local (rather than national) level and typically employs freelance wrestlers, as opposed to signing wrestlers to exclusive contracts.}}
{{term|interbrand}}
{{defn|1= A term used by [[WWE]] during [[WWE brand extension|their brand extension]] to reference a match between the [[WWE Raw|Raw]], [[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown]], or [[ECW (WWE)|ECW]] brands.}}
{{term|interpromotional}}
{{defn|1= Also known as {{gli|cross-promotion}}. A match or event involving wrestlers from two or more different promotions wrestling, usually against each other, on the same {{gli|card}}.}}
{{term|interference}}
{{defn|1= The act of someone who is not part of the match getting involved; this may involve distracting or assaulting one or more of the participants in the match.}}
{{term|invasion storyline}}
{{defn|1= A storyline in which a group of wrestlers from one promotion appear in another promotion. In some cases, this happens suddenly without advance warning or notice, and usually involves the invaders attempting to take the promotion over.}}
{{term|IWC}}
{{defn|1= Internet wrestling community; the community of [[social media]] users (some of them {{gli|smark|smarks}}) who discuss professional wrestling online on social media platforms.}}

== J ==
{{term|jerk the curtain}}
{{defn|1= To wrestle the first match of the {{gli|card}}. Refers to the curtain separating the entranceway from backstage. A wrestler commonly booked in this position is a "curtain jerker".}}
{{term|job}}
{{defn|1={{Main|Job (professional wrestling)}}
To lose in a wrestling match.}}
{{term|jobber}}
{{defn|1={{Ghat|Also '''enhancement talent'''.}}
A wrestler who routinely loses in order to build the credibility of other wrestlers.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|joshi}}
{{defn|1= Shorthand for ''joshi puroresu''; Japanese women's professional wrestling.}}
{{term|juice}}
{{defn|no=1|1= Steroids.<ref name=torch/> ''Same as {{gli|gas}}''.}}
{{defn|no=2|1= Blood,<ref name=amspeech/><ref name=race106/> usually from the forehead.<ref name=torch/> ''See also {{gli|blading}}''.}}
{{term|jumping ship}}
{{defn|1= To leave one promotion with intentions of performing in another.}}

== K ==
{{term|kayfabe}}
{{defn|1= {{Main|Kayfabe}}
The presentation of professional wrestling as being entirely legitimate or real. Prior to the mid-1980s, this was universally maintained across all wrestling territories and promotions.}}
{{term|kick-out}}
{{defn|1= To use the legs to kick or power out of a pin by using the force made to lift the shoulders off the mat.}}
{{term|King's Road}}
{{defn|1= This term describes the style of wrestling [[All Japan Pro Wrestling]] uses. It is a fusion of the Japanese {{gli|strong style}} and a more American style of professional wrestling. King's Road practitioners incorporated increasingly more {{gli|stiff}} strikes and {{gli|head drop|head drops}} during the 1990s.}}

== L ==
{{term|legit}}
{{defn|1={{Ghat|Short-form of "legitimate".}}
1.&nbsp; Refers to [[Real life|real-life]] incidents or events that have not been {{gli|book|booked}} or scripted and are therefore not part of the fictional and {{gli|kayfabe}} presentation. It is often used to describe a genuine injury to a wrestler, as opposed to one scripted as part of a storyline.}}
{{defn|no=2|1=Used to describe a wrestler with a genuine background in another combat sport (typically boxing, other wrestling codes or mixed martial arts) and so has proven "real" fighting skills.}}
{{term|lemon}}
{{defn|1= A wrestler who is not {{gli|over}} with an audience and is perceived as a failure.}}
{{term|local competitor}}
{{defn|1= An unsigned wrestler that is usually put into {{gli|squash}} matches with company wrestlers to build the other's momentum. Often used so known wrestlers from the promotion do not have to {{gli|job}}.}}
{{term|lockeroom leader|content=lockeroom leader{{anchor|link up}}}}
{{defn|1=
A veteran wrestler that peers may look to for advice or conflict resolution backstage. Usually a main eventer or long-tenured wrestler, though not exclusively. }}
{{term|lock up|content=lock up {{anchor|link up}}}}
{{defn|1={{Ghat|Also '''link up'''.}}
A portion of a match, usually the very start of the match, where two wrestler join together in a collar-and-elbow tie up.}}
{{term|low-carder}}
{{defn|1= A wrestler who typically wrestles near the beginning of a show and does not participate in major storylines or matches. Often seen as being at the bottom of a promotion's hierarchy.}}
{{term|lumberjack|content=lumberjack (m)}}
{{term|lumberjill|content=lumberjill (f)|multi=y}}
{{defn|1= A wrestler, typically, who stands close to the ring, usually in a [[lumberjack match]], in which he or she (and others similarly called upon) are to forcibly return to the ring any wrestler who attempts to leave or is expelled therefrom.  Usually, in the case of a {{gli|heel}}, he or she is actually helping one or more (rarely all) wrestlers.}}
{{term|lucha libre|''lucha libre''}}
{{defn|1= {{Main|Lucha libre}}
Mexican professional wrestling. Translates to "free fight" and is sometimes shortened to simply ''lucha'', the Mexican style of professional wrestling is characterized by high-flying aerial moves, colored masks, and the rapid series of holds, strikes, and maneuvers.}}
{{term|lucharesu|''lucharesu''}}
{{defn|1= The specific fusion style of professional wrestling that could involve the high-flying acrobatic moves of ''lucha libre'' and the suplexes, strong martial arts strikes, physicality, and psychology of ''puroresu'' or strong-style wrestling.}}

== M ==
{{term|main event}}
{{defn|1= The most heavily promoted, typically final match on a {{gli|card}}.}}
{{term|main eventer}}
{{defn|1={{Ghat|Also '''headliner'''.}}
A wrestler who wrestles in {{gli|main event|main events}}. Typically among the biggest stars in a promotion and considered to be a {{gli|draw}}.}}
{{term|manager}}
{{defn|1=[[File:Brock Lesnar and Paul Heyman April 2014.jpg|thumb|[[Paul Heyman]] (right) as {{gli|manager}} of [[Brock Lesnar]]]]
{{Main|Manager (professional wrestling)}}
A performer (usually a non-wrestler) who is paired with one or more wrestlers in order to help them get {{gli|over}}, often by acting as a {{gli|mouthpiece}} or interfering in matches on their behalf. Typically managers are seen accompanying their wrestlers to the ring and are presented as having some sort of influence or sway over their wrestlers.}}
{{term|mark}}
{{defn|no=1|1= A wrestling fan who enthusiastically believes or behaves as though professional wrestling is not staged, or loses sight of the staged nature of the business while supporting their favorite wrestlers.<ref name="Grantland">{{cite web|url= http://grantland.com/features/grantland-dictionary-pro-wrestling-edition/|title=Grantland Dictionary: Pro Wrestling Edition|work=grantland.com|date=August 13, 2014|accessdate=October 24, 2014}}</ref>  The term is often used pejoratively, for example to refer to people who have little or no knowledge about the backstage, the industry as a whole or who overzealously defend a major company or product while ignoring all others. This sub term is called a "product mark" (e.g. WWE mark, TNA mark, ROH mark; etc).}}
{{defn|no=2|1=Used by industry insiders to describe a participant in the wrestling industry who believes that any {{gli|work|worked}} aspect of the industry is more important than the money they can earn; for example, being preoccupied with holding a title belt rather than being paid more.<ref name="torch"/>}}
{{term|mechanic}}
{{defn|1=  A wrestler whose job it is to {{gli|feud}} with the future {{gli|main event}} performers and help get them ready for the position. Other times, mechanics are the in-ring teachers helping younger wrestlers gain experience and ability.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://evileye666.blogspot.com/2009/08/pro-wrestling-primer-glossary-of-terms.html|title=Pro Wrestling Primer: Glossary of terms|work=The Evil Eye Blog|date=2009|accessdate=December 7, 2014}}</ref>}}
{{term|methodical}}
{{defn|1=A wrestler who tends to work at a slower, more tactical pace as opposed to quick offense. [[Randy Orton]] is frequently described by on-air personnel as "methodical".}}
{{term|mid-carder}}
{{defn|1= A wrestler who is seen as higher than a {{gli|low-carder}}, but below a {{gli|main event|main eventer}}, typically performing in the middle of a show. Often wrestling for the secondary title of a federation. An "upper-midcarder" is a wrestler who can transition between the midcard and occasional main-event programs.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|missed spot}}
{{defn|1={{Ghat|Also '''blown spot''' and '''mis-selling'''.}}
A move or series of moves which are mistimed.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|money mark}}
{{defn|1= Someone who founds or invests in a wrestling promotion mainly to associate with wrestlers, often willfully or ignorantly disregarding financial risks a profit-focused investor would avoid. }}
{{term|money match}}
{{defn|1= A highly promoted non-title match at or near the end of a {{gli|card}}, which is a main selling point for an event.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|monster}}
{{defn|1=[[File:André the Giant in the late '80s.jpg|thumb|[[André the Giant]] was a notable {{gli|monster}} {{gli|heel}} late in his career]]
An extremely powerful, seemingly unbeatable wrestler, either {{gli|face}} or {{gli|heel}}, who often wins matches in a quick, one-sided manner.}}
{{term|mouthpiece}}
{{defn|1= A {{gli|manager}} who does the {{gli|promo|promos}}, or all the talking, for a wrestler possessing poor oration skills.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|Muta scale}}
{{defn|1= An informal measure among some fans of the amount of blood lost by a wrestler during a match. The scale begins at 0.0 Muta (no blood), with 1.0 Muta being equivalent to the blood loss of [[Keiji Mutoh|Great Muta]] during an infamous 1992 [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] match with [[Hiroshi Hase]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.411mania.com/wrestling/video_reviews/44204 |title=Complete Playbook: The Great Muta Vol. 2 Revenge of Muta Commercial Tape|first=Ryan|last=Mancuso|publisher=411mania.com|date=September 11, 2006|accessdate=October 24, 2007}}</ref>}}

== N ==
{{term|near-fall}}
{{defn|1= An occurrence in which a wrestler's shoulders are pinned to the mat for a count of two, but the wrestler manages to escape before the referee's hand hits the mat a third time, which would signify a {{gli|pinfall}}.  "Two-and-a-half count" or other fractions used to denote even closer "counts", such as "two-and-three-quarters", are often used many times in matches to build excitement.}}
{{term|night off}}
{{defn|1= To be paired for a match with a wrestler who is typically easy to work with.}}
{{term|no contest}}
{{defn|1= A match that ends in a draw without any clear resolution. This is often due to unforeseen circumstances such as an injury, a major {{gli|spot}} or {{gli|angle}} which overshadows proceedings or the referee being presented as having lost control of the match.}}
{{term|no-sell}}
{{defn|1= To show no reaction to an opponent's offensive moves; a way to demonstrate endurance, appear invulnerable to pain, legitimately undermine an opponent or to illustrate masochistic tendencies. ''Compare {{gli|sell}} and {{gli|over-sell}}''.}}
{{term|no-show}}
{{defn|1= A wrestler not showing up for a match.<ref name=torch/> No-shows can be staged for storyline purposes. Legitimate no-shows are less frequent, and the offender typically faces disciplinary action.}}
{{term|nuclear heat}}
{{defn|1= A high level of {{gli|heat}}, when fans are agitated to the point of being legitimately angry or upset.}}
{{term|number one contender}}
{{defn|1= The wrestler who is next in line for a championship match.}}

== O ==
{{term|over}}
{{defn|1= Achieving the desired crowd reaction, with the audience buying into a performer or {{gli|gimmick}}.<ref name=torch/> {{gli|face|Faces}} who are over will be cheered, and {{gli|heel|heels}} who are over will be booed. Sometimes particular aspects of a performer's presentation may be over (such as a specific chant, a move they perform or their ring entrance) without the performer themselves being considered over. Building a rapport with the audience is described as "getting over".}}
{{term|over-sell}}
{{defn|1= To show too much of a reaction to an opponent's offense. An example occurred in the match between [[Hulk Hogan]] and [[Shawn Michaels]] at [[SummerSlam (2005)|SummerSlam]] in 2005, where Michaels frequently over-sold Hogan's moves. ''Compare {{gli|sell}} and {{gli|no-sell}}''.}}

== P ==
{{term|paper}}
{{defn|1= To give out tickets to an event to make it look better attended than it otherwise would have been.}}
{{term|paper champion}}
{{defn|1= A weak or easily beaten champion, usually awarded the title by dubious means.}}
{{term|Parts Unknown}}
{{defn|1=[[File:The Ultimate Warrior April 2014.jpg|thumb|[[The Ultimate Warrior]] was popularly billed as being from {{gli|Parts Unknown}}]]
A vague, fictional location. Billing a wrestler as being from "Parts Unknown" (rather than from his real hometown or another actual place) is intended to add to a wrestler's mystique. In some territories, the phrase commonly was applied to masked wrestlers, such as [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]]. In the post-{{gli|kayfabe}} era, it is used less and less, and usually with a certain air of levity.  Sometimes, wrestlers can hail from other similarly abstract places, for example [[Cody Rhodes|Stardust]] being billed from "The 5th Dimension" or [[Damien Demento]] being billed from "The Outer Reaches of Your Mind", or may have their location simply omitted from introductions, such as in the cases of [[Big Show]] and [[Braun Strowman]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Cory Kilgannon|title=From Inside a Bad-Guy Wrestler, a Brutal Artist Screamed for Release|website=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 15, 2012|url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/03/15/from-inside-a-bad-guy-wrestler-a-brutal-artist-screamed-for-release/|accessdate=January 14, 2016}}</ref>}}
{{term|payoff}}
{{defn|1= The culmination of an {{gli|angle}} or storyline with the intention of providing gratification for the fans. Typically involves a {{gli|face}} finally overcoming a dominant {{gli|heel}}.}}
{{term|Philly pop}}
{{defn|1= The act of a promotion bringing in a former [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]] wrestler when in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]].}}
{{term|pinfall}}
{{defn|1={{Main|Pin (professional wrestling)}} 
Holding a wrestler's shoulders to the mat for a three count, to win a {{gli|fall}}.}}
{{term|pipe bomb}}
{{defn|1= A {{gli|worked shoot}} {{gli|promo}} where the wrestler giving the promo appears to break {{gli|kayfabe}} and touches on real-life topics that are considered taboo, such as backstage politics or issues which are not typically addressed in storylines due to bad publicity. This was a term first used by [[CM Punk]].{{Citation Needed|date=August 2017}}}}
{{term|plant}}
{{defn|1= A wrestler or actor who poses as a fan, usually seated in the front row of an event.<ref name=torch/> Plants are often victimized or attacked used by {{gli|heel}} wrestlers in order to gain {{gli|heat}}, or are used to participate in matches or storylines after being "randomly selected" from the crowd.<ref name=torch/> Notable examples of plants were the [[WWE]] debut of [[Santino Marella]], who won the [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|Intercontinental Championship]] after being picked out of the crowd, or at [[WrestleMania 34]] when a 10 year old boy named Nicholas (in reality the son of referee [[John Cone]]) was chosen by [[Braun Strowman]] to be his tag team partner in his match against [[Cesaro and Sheamus]].<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MKe0WEAI4eM|title=Young WWE fan Nicholas teams with Braun Strowman against The Bar|publisher=[[WWE]]|website=''[[YouTube]]''|date=April 8, 2018|accessdate=April 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alfredkonuwa/2018/04/08/wwe-wrestlemania-34-results-braun-strowman-picks-10-year-old-wwe-fan-nicholas-as-mystery-partner/|title=WWE WrestleMania 34 results: Braun Strowman picks 10 year old WWE fan 'Nicholas' as mystery partner|publisher=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=9 April 2018}}</ref>}}
{{term|policeman}}
{{term|police woman|multi=y}}
{{defn|1={{Ghat|Also '''house shooter'''.}}
A wrestler, often a respected or feared shooter or street fighter, responsible for enforcing the promoter's will against recalcitrant wrestlers by performing unscripted or painful moves within a match, punishing or intimidating them for defying the management. In today's industry it is a largely outdated because such tactics are illegal if they can be proved. Typically it is only still used by {{gli|dirt sheets}} and outside commentators who believe one wrestler is deliberately placed in matches against more dangerous opponents and injured deliberately after disagreements with management. While allegations of this sort persist, including being made by wrestlers themselves, few have been proven.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|pop}}
{{defn|1= A cheer or positive reaction from the crowd.}}
{{term|potato}}
{{defn|1= A strike to the head which makes real contact. A wrestler who endures one or more potatoes is likely to potato the perpetrator back, which is known as a {{gli|receipt}}.}}
{{term|powdering}}
{{defn|1= The act of forcefully exiting the ring.}}
{{term|program}}
{{defn|1= A series of matches in which the same wrestlers face each other, usually due to the two being scripted in a {{gli|feud}}.}}
{{term|promo}}
{{defn|1=[[File:Thecabinet.jpg|thumb|[[John Layfield|John "Bradshaw" Layfield]] (right) cutting a {{gli|promo}}]]
An in-character interview or monologue.<ref name=torch/> Often includes either an "in-ring interview" or (on television) a skit by wrestlers and other performers to advance a storyline or {{gli|feud}}.<ref name=torch/> The act of performing a promo is referred to as "cutting", as in "cutting a promo". When the promo is aimed at a specific opponent (which can be an individual, team, stable or faction), it is said to be cut "on" the target. }}
{{term|protected}}
{{defn|1= An aspect of the business which is consciously presented in a way that will made it look as strong and credible as possible. Wrestlers can be protected by {{gli|book|booking}} them in a way which emphasizes their strengths and hides their weaknesses as a performer, while a move can be protected by having opponents {{gli|sell}} strongly and rarely {{gli|kick out}}.}}
{{term|pull apart}} 
{{defn|1= A brawl so vicious that the combatants need to be pulled apart by others. }}
{{term|put over}}
{{defn|1= The act of one wrestler helping to boost the status of another, most often by losing a match or by {{gli|sell|selling}} their opponent as a credible threat.}}
{{term|puroresu|content=''puroresu''}}
{{defn|1={{Main|Puroresu}}
Japanese professional wrestling. The term can be transliterated as "pro-wres".}}
{{term|push}}
{{defn|1= {{Main|Push (professional wrestling)}}
The {{gli|work|worked}} rising of a wrestler's status in the eyes of the fans.}}

== R ==
{{term|rasslin'}}
{{defn|1={{Ghat|Also '''wrasslin'''', '''southern style''', or more specifically, '''Memphis style'''.}}
Originally, along with "grunt-and-groan", used by the mainstream media when presenting a derisive story on professional wrestling, which often stereotyped the participants and audience. Now refers to a style of wrestling popular in [[Memphis, Tennessee]], and as a result, the [[southeastern United States]], which emphasizes {{gli|kayfabe}} and {{gli|stiff|stiffness}}, generally with fewer {{gli|squash}} matches and longer {{gli|feud|feuds}}, hence the more recent "southern style" or to be specific compared to the Jim Crockett or Georgia styles, "Memphis style".}}
{{term|receipt}}
{{defn|1= A term for returning a particularly {{gli|stiff}} move back to a wrestler.}}
{{term|ref bump}}
{{defn|1= A scenario where the referee of the match takes a {{gli|bump}} and is knocked out and taken out of the match, temporarily or permanently. This usually occurs to allow a storyline to progress.}}
{{term|rematch clause|2=rematch clause {{anchor|return clause}}}}
{{defn|1={{Ghat|Also '''return clause'''.}}
When a champion loses his or her title to another, this may be invoked to procure a title rematch in the near future. This fictional clause is often ignored in storylines.}}
{{term|repackage}}
{{defn|1= To give a wrestler a new {{gli|gimmick}}.}}
{{term|rest hold}}
{{defn|1=[[File:Ted DiBiase headlock on Daniel Bryan.jpg|thumb|[[Ted DiBiase Jr.]] performing a {{gli|rest hold}} on [[Daniel Bryan]]]]
A loose hold applied during a match, during which wrestlers catch their breath or plan the next series of {{gli|spot|spots}} together.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|rib}}
{{defn|1= A practical joke played by or on a wrestler.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|ring general}}
{{defn|1= An experienced wrestler who knows how to work a match to its full potential.}}
{{term|ring psychology}}
{{defn|1= The process of wrestling a match in such a way that the crowd becomes emotionally involved. Performing an engaging match requires acting skills and a good grasp of dramatic timing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/SlamWrestlingBiosB/booker_00jun18.html|title=Booker T: Wrestling's consummate performer|author=John Powell|publisher=SLAM! Wrestling|accessdate=2008-06-17|date=June 18, 2000}}</ref>}}
{{term|ring rat}}
{{defn|1= Similar to a [[groupie]], one who frequents wrestling events to pursue sex with wrestlers.<ref name=torch/><ref>{{cite book|last=Laurer |first=Joanie |authorlink=Chyna |title=If They Only Knew |pages=192–193}}</ref>}}
{{term|ring rust}}
{{defn|1= A detriment to wrestling ability resulting from lack of practice during a hiatus.}}
{{term|rub}}
{{defn|1= Helping a less popular wrestler get {{gli|over}} by associating them with a more prominent or popular wrestler.<ref name='jrosschristmas'>{{cite web|url = http://www.jrsbarbq.com/blog/rawchristmas-feedback-bobby-eaton-hospitalized-paul-finebaum-tenaytaz-glory-sports-ufc-ppv|title=#RAW Christmas Feedback...|accessdate=December 25, 2013|last1=Ross|first1=Jim|author2=J.R.'s Family Bar-B-Q®|authorlink=Jim Ross|date=December 24, 2013|work=J.R.'s Place blog}}</ref>}}
{{term|run-in}}
{{defn|1=[[File:NWo WM31.jpg|thumb|The [[New World Order (professional wrestling)|nWo]] performing a {{gli|run-in}} during [[WrestleMania 31]]]]
The unexpected entry of a new wrestler(s) or returning wrestler in a match already in progress.<ref name=torch/> Run-ins are usually made by {{gli|heel|heels}}, typically to further a {{gli|feud}} with a {{gli|face}}.<ref name=torch/> This is usually done with a {{gli|beat down}}. Sometimes a face will do a run-in to stop a heel from overly punishing a weaker opponent, usually setting up a feud.}}
{{term|rushed finish}}
{{defn|1= A match finish which occurs sooner (and often differently) than planned. It is used when a wrestler is legitimately injured and cannot continue as planned, when the match is approaching its time limit (or a television segment is running long), or after a {{gli|botch}} significantly changes the plot of the match.}}

== S ==
{{term|sandbag}}
{{defn|1= To sabotage a [[Professional wrestling throws|throw]] by letting one's body go limp instead of cooperating, which makes the throw much harder, if not impossible, to execute. This move is typically done deliberately to make the attacker appear weak or unskilled, but can also be the result of a {{gli|botch}}. Sandbagging can be dangerous, as many moves require specific actions by the target to lower the risk of injury.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|schmoz}}
{{defn|1= A crowd of wrestlers in a brawl, designed to end a match or {{gli|angle}}.}}
{{term|school}}
{{defn|1= A place where professional wrestlers are trained. These may be beginner schools with classes open to the general public, or high-end facilities operated by major companies (such as the [[WCW Power Plant]], [[WWE Performance Center]], TNA's [[Al Snow|Al Snow Wrestling Academy]], or the [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling|New Japan Dojo]]) that accept students on an invitation-only basis.}}
{{term|screwjob}}
{{defn|1= An unfair and controversial finish, often involving cheating or outside interference.<ref name=torch/> A {{gli|work|worked}} screwjob is part of the story, and is used to generate heat or sympathy. A {{gli|shoot}} screwjob occurs when the finish is changed without informing the losing wrestler. One famous instance of this was the [[Montreal Screwjob]] at the 1997 [[Survivor Series (1997)|Survivor Series]], when [[Shawn Michaels]] won the [[WWE Championship|WWF Championship]] from [[Bret Hart]].}}
{{term|second}}
{{defn|1= A person accompanying, or "seconding", a wrestler to a match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=111905&p=3|title=AAA Triplemania 2017 today, complete lineup|accessdate=18 December 2017|work=Pro Wrestling Insider}}</ref> Often a {{gli|manager}} or a {{gli|valet}}.}}
{{term|sell}}
{{defn|1= To react to something in a way that makes it appear believable and legitimate to the audience.<ref name=torch/> Typically refers to the physical action of making an opponent's moves look impactful, but it can be used to refer to any aspect of the {{gli|work|worked}} presentation.<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2V060IwjJh4&t=1m35s|title=X-Pac on: Yokozuna|date=31 December 2014|work=YouTube}}</ref> ''Compare {{gli|no-sell}} and {{gli|over-sell}}''.}}
{{term|shoot}}
{{defn|1={{Main|Shoot (professional wrestling)}}
When a wrestler or personality deliberately goes off-script, either by making candid comments or remarks during an interview, breaking {{gli|kayfabe}}, or {{gli|legit|legitimately}} attacking an opponent.}}
{{term|shoot style}}
{{defn|1={{Main|Shoot wrestling}}
A style of professional wrestling that originates in Japan. Shoot style wrestling employs {{gli|stiff}} strikes, realistic [[submission holds]], and occasionally a round system or other specific rules and ways to win in an attempt to give professional wrestling a {{gli|legit|legitimate}} sports-like feel. [[Satoru Sayama]] and [[Akira Maeda]] in the [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Japan)|UWF]] and [[Nobuhiko Takada]] in the [[UWF International|UWFi]] popularized the style.}} 
{{term|signature move}}
{{defn|1= A move a wrestler regularly performs, for which the wrestler is well known.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Hardy Boyz: Pro Wrestlers Matt and Jeff Hardy|first=Angie Peterson|last=Kaelberer|publisher=Capstone Press|year=2003|isbn=0-7368-2142-2|page=44}}</ref>}}
{{term|skit}}
{{defn|1= Any part of a wrestling show that is not a wrestling match, such as a {{gli|promo}}, a comedy sketch, or an interview.}}
{{term|slow burn}}
{{defn|1= A storyline that develops over a long period.}}
{{term|smark}}
{{defn|1= Short for "smart {{gli|mark}}". Someone who has inside knowledge of the wrestling business, but is not speaking from their own personal experience with the business. Often used as a term of derision for know-it-all fans.<ref name="Grantland"/>}}
{{term|smart}}
{{defn|1= Having inside knowledge of the wrestling business. Originally used to refer to those who were aware of the existence of {{gli|kayfabe}} and the scripted nature of professional wrestling. The act of teaching someone inside knowledge of the wrestling business is referred to as 'smartening up' someone.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|snug}}
{{defn|1= To apply real pressure to a hold, either to make it appear more realistic to the audience, or to exact supremacy or revenge over an opponent.<ref name="Grantland"/> ''Compare {{gli|stiff}}''.}}
{{term|sports entertainment}}
{{defn|1={{Ghat|{{Main|Sports entertainment}}}}
The term [[WWE]] uses to describe both its own product and professional wrestling as a whole. It was first used by the promotion in the 1980s and is intended to acknowledge wrestling's roots in competitive sport and dramatic theater.}}
{{term|spot}}
{{defn|1= Any planned action or series of actions in a match.<ref name=torch/> Variations include the {{gli|highspot}}, {{gli|comeback|comeback spot}}, {{gli|hope spot}} and take home spot. ''Compare {{gli|missed spot}}''.}}
{{term|spotfest}}
{{defn|1= A match which consists mainly or entirely of pre-planned {{gli|spot|spots}}, normally with little flow and no logical transitions between moves and with little or no or story-telling. Often used as a derisory term for matches which are seen to prioritize high-impact stunts over {{gli|ring psychology}}.}}
{{term|spotmonkey}}
{{defn|1= Derogatory term used to denote a wrestler who is believed to rely heavily on {{gli|highspot|highspots}} in order to mask a lack of basic wrestling ability.}}
{{term|squared circle}}
{{defn|1= The wrestling ring.}}
{{term|squash}}
{{defn|1= An extremely one-sided match.<ref name=torch/> Sometimes called [[Tomato can (sports idiom)|Tomato-can]] match. Squashes generally feature star wrestlers or wrestlers receiving a {{gli|push}} quickly and easily defeating {{gli|job|jobbers}}, usually to help get a {{gli|gimmick}} or moveset {{gli|over}}.}}
{{term|stable}}
{{defn|1=[[File:The Shield's fist pose.jpg|thumb|{{gli|stable|Stables}} can vary in size, from three-man units like [[The Shield (professional wrestling)|The Shield]] (pictured) to large groups with varying membership such as the [[New World Order (professional wrestling)|nWo]] or [[Bullet Club]]]]
A team of three or more wrestlers, usually {{gli|heel|heels}}, who generally share common motives, allies and adversaries within a storyline (or through multiple storylines) and are often presented as having the same or very similar {{gli|gimmick|gimmicks}}. Stables sometimes have several members partake in more separate activities, such as [[Owen Hart and the British Bulldog]] having their own tag team while also being part of the larger [[Hart Foundation]].}}
{{term|stiff}}
{{defn|1= Using excessive force when executing a move, deliberately or accidentally.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|Sting money}}
{{defn|1= A term from the 1990s used to refer to a lucrative contract, such as the one held by [[Sting (wrestler)|Sting]] in [[World Championship Wrestling]].<ref>{{cite episode|title=The nWo|series=[[WWE Legends of Wrestling|Legends of Wrestling]]|network=[[WWE Classics on Demand|Classics on Demand]]|station=[[WWE]]|date=1 July 2011|season=1|number=28|minutes=2}}</ref>}}
{{term|strap}}
{{defn|1= A championship belt.}}
{{term|stretching}}
{{defn|1= The act of causing physical harm to prospective professional wrestlers, usually by the means of [[submission holds]]. In the {{gli|kayfabe}} period, this served the dual purpose of protecting the wrestling business from accusations of "being fake" and instilling humility in newer members of the locker room. A professional wrestling trainer notable for "stretching" his recruits was [[Stu Hart]], in the infamous [[Hart Dungeon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://offthetracks.co.nz/heart-to-hart-90-minutes-on-the-phone-with-bret-the-hitman-hart/|title=Heart to Hart: 90 Minutes on the Phone with Bret ‘The Hitman’ Hart|website=offthetracks.co.nz}}</ref> Other wrestlers in various territories who were used to test potential newcomers were [[Danny Hodge]], [[Bob Roop]], and [["Dr. Death" Steve Williams]].}}
{{term|strike}}
{{defn|no=1|1= Any contact made by one wrestler to their opponent (e.g. punches, kicks, chops; etc.).}}
{{defn|no=2|1= A violation of [[WWE]]'s wellness policy, with three strikes in an 18-month period resulting in a wrestler being released from the promotion.}}
{{term|strong style}}
{{defn|1= A Japanese-inspired professional wrestling style that is {{gli|work|worked}}, yet aims to deliver realistic performances, through {{gli|stiff}} martial arts strikes and {{gli|worked shoot|worked shoots}}.<ref name=torch/>}}
{{term|super finisher}}
{{defn|1= A move rarely used by a wrestler, but one that almost always ends a match. A notable example is [[Randy Orton]]'s Punt Kick.}}
{{term|Superstar}}
{{defn|1= [[WWE]]'s term for wrestlers on their roster.}}
{{term|swerve}}
{{defn|1= A sudden change in the direction of a storyline to surprise the fans. Often, it involves one wrestler {{gli|turn|turning}} on an ally in order to join a supposed mutual enemy. Swerves frequently start {{gli|feud|feuds}} between the former allies. This also refers to when a {{gli|book|booker}} leads fans to believe that something is going to happen (or someone could appear) at a show, before doing something entirely different.<ref name=torch/>}}

== T ==
{{term|tap out}}
{{defn|1= To submit to a hold by tapping on the mat (or the attacker's body), as in mixed martial arts, rather than verbally submitting, as was standard in professional wrestling until [[Ken Shamrock]] popularized tapping out in 1997. The tapout was introduced to professional wrestling shortly earlier by [[Tazz]].<ref name=only152>{{cite book|last=Laurer|first=Joanie|title=If They Only Knew|page=152}}</ref> Tapping out may have also become more the norm thanks to the [[Montreal Screwjob]].}}
{{term|tease}}
{{defn|1= To indicate a {{gli|turn}}. A {{gli|face}} teases a {{gli|heel}} turn if he/she starts exhibiting heel behaviors and a heel indicates a face turn if he/she starts exhibiting face behaviors.}}
{{term|technician}}
{{defn|1= A wrestler who employs or masters so called [[technical wrestling]] style. [[Bret Hart]] is a commonly cited example of a great technical wrestler.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whatculture.com/wwe/10-greatest-wrestling-technicians-in-wwe-history|title=10 Greatest Wrestling Technicians In WWE History|first=Erik|last=Beaston|date=17 April 2016|website=WhatCulture.com}}</ref>}}
{{term|Titan Tower}}
{{defn|A nickname for [[WWE]]'s corporate office in [[Stamford, Connecticut]].}}
{{term|TitanTron}}
{{defn|1=[[File:Christian v Orton at MITB 2011.jpg|thumb|The {{gli|TitanTron}} (background) at [[Money in the Bank (2011)|Money in the Bank]] in July 2011]]
A video screen above the entrance stage area, used for showing entrance videos, backstage segments, and promos. A play on the name of [[Sony]]'s [[JumboTron]] and [[WWE#Titan Sports|Titan Sports]], the then-parent company of the [[World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF), the TitanTron was introduced as part of WWF's ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'' set in the mid-1990s. The concept has since been adapted by other major promotions, such as [[World Championship Wrestling]], who used the TurnerTron.}}
{{term|title shot}}
{{defn|1=The opportunity to face a reigning champion in a match in which their championship is on the line and can change hands.}}
{{term|transitional champion}}
{{defn|1= A short-reigning champion who serves to move the title indirectly from one wrestler to a third. They are usually used when the title is to be moved between two faces, to avoid requiring them to wrestle each other.}}
{{term|turn}}
{{defn|1= A switch in alignment of a wrestler's character. Turns involve a wrestler going from {{gli|face}} to {{gli|heel}} or vice versa.<ref name=torch/> There are two types of turns, the hard turn (which occurs quickly and acts as a surprise device) and the soft turn (a gradual shift in character).}}
{{term|tweener}}
{{defn|1= A morally ambiguous wrestler who is neither a {{gli|face}} nor {{gli|heel}} (an in-betweener),<ref name=torch/> also sometimes describes a heel who is usually cheered or a face who is usually jeered, especially when two faces or two heels face each other.}}

== U ==
{{term|unified|content=unified {{anchor|Unified}}}}
{{defn|1={{see also|Championship unification}}
The state of two or more [[championship (professional wrestling)|championships]] when merged by one champion.}}

== V ==
{{term|vacant|content=vacant {{anchor|Vacated}}}}
{{defn|1= The state of a [[championship (professional wrestling)|championship]] not held by any wrestlers.}}
{{term|valet}}
{{defn|1=
[[File:Enzo Cass Carmella.jpg|thumb|[[Enzo Amore]] [[Enzo and Cass|and]] [[Big Cass|Colin Cassady]] with their {{gli|valet}} [[Carmella (wrestler)|Carmella]]]]
A person, usually an attractive female, who accompanies a male performer to the ring.<ref name=stomp>{{cite web|url=http://www.stompandstammer.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=986&Itemid=51&limit=1&limitstart=0|title= The Luchagors Drop a Powerbomb|author=Jeff Clark|publisher=Stomp and Stammer|accessdate=2007-10-02|date=September 7, 2007}}</ref> Usually serves to titillate or agitate the crowd, or to {{gli|interference|interfere}} in the match.<ref name=stomp/>}}
{{term|vanilla midget}}
{{defn|1= A derogatory term created by [[Kevin Nash]] to describe wrestlers who were good ring-workers but he believed to be too small or boring to ever succeed on a large stage.}}
{{term|vignette}}
{{defn|1= Any piece of video footage featuring characters or events which is shown to the audience for the purposes of entertainment or edification. Usually meant to introduce a debuting character or to get a wrestler {{gli|over}} before their TV wrestling debut.}}
{{term|visual fall}}
{{defn|1= A {{gli|pinfall}} that the referee does not see, but the crowd does. It is usually followed by a late {{gli|kick-out}} when the referee eventually sees the pinfall and starts counting. It is used to heighten the drama of a match by showing that the pinning wrestler "would have had him".}}

== W ==
{{term|work}}
{{defn|no=1|1=(noun): Anything planned to happen,<ref name=amspeech/> or a "rationalized lie".<ref name=torch/> The opposite of {{gli|shoot}}.}}
{{defn|no=2|1=(verb): To methodically attack a single body part, setting up an appropriate {{gli|finisher}}.}}
{{defn|no=3|1=(verb): To deceive or manipulate an audience in order to illicit a desired response.}}
{{term|worked shoot}}
{{defn|1= The phenomenon of a wrestler seemingly going "off script", often revealing elements of out-of-universe reality, but actually doing so as a fully planned part of the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grantland.com/story/_/id/6712903/punkd|title=Punk'd|author=The Masked Man (David Shoemaker)|website=[[Grantland]]|date=June 28, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130121052600/http://www.grantland.com/story/_/id/6712903/punkd|archivedate=January 21, 2013}}</ref>}}
{{term|worker}}
{{defn|1= Another term for professional wrestler. Often used in the context of describing in-ring skill level (e.g. "He is a good/bad worker").}}
{{term|workrate}}
{{defn|1= The in-ring performance level a wrestler puts into their matches, judged by a combination of skill and effort. A wrestler considered talented in the ring has a "high workrate".}}
{{term|wrestler's court}}
{{defn|1= A term used often to describe [[kangaroo court]]s held backstage with a congregation of wrestlers; this is often used to settle backstage disputes between performers.}}

== X ==
{{term|X Division}}
{{defn|1=A high-flying, high-risk, fast-paced style of professional wrestling which was originated in [[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]] (TNA). Rather than emphasizing the fact that most wrestlers who perform this style are under 220 lb (100 kg) by calling it a [[Cruiserweight (professional wrestling)|cruiserweight]] division, they decided to emphasize the high-risk nature of the moves that these wrestlers perform, removing all restraints were placed on its wrestlers, allowing them to perform almost stunt-like wrestling moves.}}
{{term|X signal}}
{{defn|1= A signal used by referees during a match to indicate that a wrestler is unable to continue and may need medical attention. The referee will cross his arms and, if necessary, point to the injured wrestler. Since many fans are aware of the significance of the signal, and with referees often now having direct communication with producers backstage, it is now sometimes used in {{gli|kayfabe}} fashion, to {{gli|sell}} a storyline injury.}}
{{term|x-pac heat|content=X-Pac heat {{anchor|X-Pac heat}}}}
{{defn|1= When fans boo a wrestler because they dislike the wrestler personally as opposed to the character he or she plays in the ring. Named after [[Sean Waltman]], known as X-Pac, who was believed to have "overstayed his welcome" by some fans, and so was booed regardless of whether he was a {{gli|face}} or {{gli|heel}} character.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reference.com/sports-active-lifestyle/x-pac-heat-8dc6c2fa2b042bb6|title=What is "X-Pac heat"?|website=[[Reference.com]]}}</ref> ''Compare {{gli|go away heat}}''.}}

== Y ==
{{term|young boy}}{{anchor|Young lion}}
{{defn|1={{Ghat|Also '''young lion'''.}}
A rookie, particularly in Japanese professional wrestling. Also referred to as young lions for the trainees at the [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] dojo.}}
{{glossary end}}

